question:
it says that "Unhandled Runtime Error
Error: Objects are not valid as a React child (found: [object Promise]). If you meant to render a collection of children, use an array instead." for the following code
"use client";

import React from "react";
import { updateOrder } from "@/app/BookAPI";
import Link from "next/link";
import { useState } from "react";

const page = async ({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) => {
 const { id } = params;

 const [customerName, setCustomerName] = useState("");

 const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
 e.preventDefault();
 const orderStatus = await updateOrder(id, customerName);
 console.log(orderStatus);
 };

 return (


 Update Order
============




 Customer Name
 setCustomerName(e.target.value)}
 />

 Update Order

 );
};

export default page;

answer:
The error message you're encountering is due to trying to render a Promise object in React, which is not allowed. In your current code, the `handleSubmit` function is an `async` function, meaning it returns a Promise. When you call `console.log(orderStatus)`, you're trying to log the Promise, which leads to the error.

To fix this, you should handle the Promise properly by using `.then()` and `.catch()` methods, or use `async/await` syntax to ensure that the Promise is resolved before trying to log its value. Here's an updated version of your `handleSubmit` function that uses `async/await` syntax:
```javascript
const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  try {
    const orderStatus = await updateOrder(id, customerName);
    console.log(orderStatus);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
};
```
This code uses a `try/catch` block to handle any errors that may occur while waiting for the Promise to resolve. If the Promise resolves successfully, the `orderStatus` variable will contain its value, which can then be logged to the console. If an error occurs, it will be caught and logged to the console as well.

