Please use rayon to parallelize `find_duplicates`

answer:
Here is the function `find_duplicates` parallelized using Rayon:

```rust
use rayon::prelude::*;

fn find_duplicates(videos: HashMap<u32, Video>) {
    let mut phashes: Vec<Phash> = videos
        .iter()
        .flat_map(|(&video_id, video)| {
            video.phash.iter().map(move |&phash| Phash {
                video_id,
                phash,
                neighbors: HashSet::new(),
            })
        })
        .collect();

    let max_distance: u32 = 6;

    phashes.par_iter_mut().enumerate().for_each(|(i, query)| {
        phashes.par_iter_mut().enumerate().for_each(|(j, item)| {
            if i == j || query.neighbors.contains(&j) || query.video_id == item.video_id {
                return;
            }

            let distance = (query.phash ^ item.phash).count_ones();
            if distance <= max_distance {
                query.neighbors.insert(j);
                item.neighbors.insert(i);
            }
        });
    });
}
```

This version of the function creates a vector of `Phash` instances, then uses Rayon's `par_iter_mut` to iterate over the vector in parallel. The `enumerate` function is used to keep track of the index of each `Phash` instance. This allows for efficient comparison of all pairs of `Phash` instances while avoiding data races.

