answer:
To support Windows, you can modify the code to check for the "Control" key instead of the "Meta" key. Here's the updated code:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const handleKeyDown = (event) => {
    // Check if the CTRL + F key combination was pressed
    if (event.key === "f" && event.ctrlKey) {
      event.preventDefault();

      setIsShown(true);
    }
  };

  window.addEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);

  return () => {
    window.removeEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);
  };
}, [setExclusionFilter]);
```

In this updated code, we changed `event.metaKey` to `event.ctrlKey` to detect the CTRL key on Windows. Now the code should work on both Windows and Mac.

